What are your favorite 3D printed parts for FRC? General Forum
This could be parts specifically for robots, assembling robots, used in the pits, or even something for driver stations. I got a lot of extra filament and a lot of time during break! Give me your ideas.
3d printing usage Technical
Our team have had access to 3d printers for quite some time now and we have always only used them for printing shaft spacers and some blocks here and there. I’ve always had the feeling that we could do much more then that but never saw any other useful ways to actually use them. So I wanted to hear how other teams use their 3d printers. share away
Designing and Producing 3D Printed Parts Manufacturing
My teams currently dependent on a small handful of people when it comes to 3D printing parts, so I’m trying to develop a few lessons for people on how to design for 3D printed parts, how to use a 3D printer, and understanding their limits, etc. How do your teams typically design for 3D printed parts? What filaments do you use for different applications? Any other info that might be useful? Edit: What do you do to account for 3D Printing fumes as well? I know most people don’t worry about it to…

We print a significant portion of our robot tbh. All of our timeing belt pullies, an increasing number of gears and spacers, a number of gussets and other assorted mounts including core structural components, and stuff like sensor/camera mounts. During the season our print farm is running practically 24/7.

As far as materuals go we almost exclusively use PA6-CF or PA12-CF, we do not use any PLA parts in comp.

Things that made it onto our 2024 robot, which was a glorified Kitbot:

  • Spacers on our Everybot amp mechanism
  • Pulleys for the Everybot amp mechanism (used with Thrifty adapters)
  • A null stage for the MAXPlanetary gearboxes we used with no gear reduction, so that the NEO shaft wouldn’t hit the output shaft.
  • Shaft spacers for the shooter NEOs, so the MAXPlanetary spline engaged well with the output stage spline.

We also did test prints on other things that didn’t make the cut, including a one-piece standoff for the intake motor, gears to make the intake rollers counter-rotate, and we printed the Kitbot shooter plates for a mockup while waiting on a late resupply from AndyMark (we initially opted out and this was a too-late late pivot).

All of that was in the Protopasta recycled PLA that was available for dirt cheap from the KoP voucher. It’s good stuff at a great price.

Just about everything.
Gears.
Pulleys.
Motor/gear mounts and housings.
Brackets.
Shooter backplane.
Camera housings.
Just about every part of our swerve.

I think the main reason people make TPU tread is because it has a better CoF than nitrile. In our experience, it actually wears faster than nitrile tread needing to be swapped every like 3-4 games vs nitrile able to last like twice that.

This year we printing timing belts from TPU for prototype mechanisms. This was game changing for us as we couldn’t afford to just have a stock of every size on hand and this allowed us to have any size we wanted. When the design was finalised we swapped them out for ‘real’ belts.

The other ‘use’ for 3D printing is that it is a good place to start getting students doing CAD design. CAD beginners can design small parts, such as camera mounts, in isolation before they are ready for dealing with the full robot CAD.
